<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12027d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12027d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12027d"> 27(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> toad (avare) afraid to eat / too much earth</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">(Il est) de la race du crapaud qui craint qu&apos;&agrave; manger la terre ne lui manque (1). <br><font color="green">[He belongs to the race of the toads who is afraid to eat earth because it may run out]</font> <br>Note 1: Ce proverbe s&apos;applique aux avares. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> sur les &eacute;tranges tableaux dont se servent les pr&eacute;dicateurs bretons <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> l&apos;avarice est repr&eacute;sent&eacute;e sous la forme du crapaud qui, dit-on, n&apos;ose manger plein son ventre de terre, de crainte qu&apos;elle ne vienne &agrave; lui manquer <br><font color="green">[This proverb is applied to misers. On the strange pictures used by Breton preachers, avarice is represented by a toad, who, they say, does not dare to fill its belly with earth, for fear there will not be enough.]</font> <small> L-F. Sauv&eacute, <a name="LFSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LFSP"><cite title="source">Proverbes et dictons de la Basse-Bretagne</cite></a> (1878) 51</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
